06891nam a22010455i 9783110219234DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979731450  a97831102192347 a10.1515/97831102192342doi  a(DE-B1597)36645  a(OCoLC)635962063  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aPhonology in Perception /ced. by Paul Boersma, Silke Hamann. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (318 p.) :bFigs. and tabs.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhonology and Phonetics [PP] ,x1861-4191 ;v1500tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction: models of phonology in perception -- tWhy can Poles perceive Sprite but not Coca-Cola? A Natural Phonological account -- tCue constraints and their interactions in phonological perception and production -- tThe learner of a perception grammar as a source of sound change -- tThe linguistic perception of SIMILAR L2 sounds -- tStress adaptation in loanword phonology: perception and learnability -- tPerception of intonational contours on given and new referents: a completion study and an eyemovement experiment -- tLexical access, effective contrast, and patterns in the lexicon -- tPhonology and perception: a cognitive scientist’s perspective -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe book consists of nine chapters dealing with the interaction of speech perception and phonology. Rather than accepting the common assumption that perceptual considerations influence phonological behaviour, the book aims to investigate the reverse direction of causation, namely the extent to which phonological knowledge guides the speech perception process. Most of the chapters discuss formalizations of the speech perception process that involve ranked phonological constraints. Theoretical frameworks argued for are Natural Phonology, Optimality Theory, and the Neigbourhood Activation Model. The book discusses the perception of segments, stress, and intonation in the fields of loanword adaptation, second language acquisition, and sound change. The book is of interest to phonologists, phoneticians and psycholinguists working on the phonetics-phonology interface, and to everybody who is interested in the idea that phonology is not production alone.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aPhonologie. 4aPsycholinguistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aPhonology.  aPsycholinguistics.1 aBalas, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoersma, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoersma, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBroselow, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscudero, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFéry, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamann, Silke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamann, Silke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHörnig, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaiser, Elsi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKliegl, Reinhold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClelland, James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUssishkin, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWedel, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeskott, Thomas, econtr